SIMPLE: whitewash
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Whitewash
<hw>White"wash`</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Any wash or liquid composition for whitening
something, as a wash for making the skin fair.</def>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A composition of line and water, or of whiting size,
and water, or the like, used for whitening walls, ceilings, etc.; milk
of lime.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>a glossing over or cover up (of crimes or
misfeasance).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whitewash</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Whitewash
<hw>White"wash`</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Whitewashed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Whitewashing</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To apply a white liquid composition to; to whiten
with whitewash.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make white; to give a fair external appearance
to; to clear from imputations or disgrace; hence, to clear (a bankrupt)
from obligation to pay debts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>In various games, to defeat (an opponent) so that he
fails to score, or to reach a certain point in the game; to skunk.</def>
<mark>[Colloq., U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>to gloss over or cover up (crimes or
misfeasance).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whitewasher</ent>⟦br⟧
